\par Marilyn:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
Well, as I think I mentioned in the interview with Alan Macfarlane, I was on one of the little expeditions that Audrey Richards arranged to visit the village she was living in \endash  Elmdon \endash  which is not
 far outside Cambridge, so that we could practice field-like skills, as it were. She\rquote 
d come back from a long period in East Africa, settled in this small village, and made many comparisons between village life in the parts of Africa that she knew, and what appeared to be English village life. And we\rquote 
re talking of the late 1950s/1960s, and places really were quite insular, quite isolated, so that Elmdon, for example, would differentiate itself from Duddenhoe End, which was a mile and a half away, that kind o
f thing, and she saw many parallels with village life, as she knew it, in other places. And forever the anthropologist, set about collecting bits and pieces of information from people. [She] then teamed up with Edmund Leach \endash  I don\rquote 
t know if I mentioned that in the interview \endash  for a while, because Edmund, having worked in Sri Lanka \endash  Ceylon as it then was \endash  on land tenure and kinship, was very interested in the whole issue of people\rquote 
s ownership of material needs, especially land. He had a running controvers
y with Meyer Fortes, who was also in the Department, because Edmund regarded kinship - statements about kinship as ideology - that dealt with what were basically economic or political economic issues, and Meyer Fortes thought that kinship was a sui generi
s
 form of social organisation. So, I mean, they had this argument, and it was because Edmund was involved in that argument that he could see the point of going to places like Elmdon and look at property, looking at especially the farms, who owned the land,
 and so forth. Edmund Leach and Audrey Richards were of very different temperament, and the alliance didn\rquote 
t last very long, but, nevertheless, it was stimulating while it did. All right. So over the years, Audrey amassed quite a bit of data, sometimes by ha
ving small groups of students, as the group that I was with, stay for a little while; sometimes putting someone up from \endash  because she had us all up in her house \endash 
 putting up someone for a longer period; people also lived in Elmdon for shorter or longer periods. I went off to work in Papua New Guinea. To and fro a bit, but eventually back in the UK in 1976. By that time, Audrey had moved \endash 
 she was getting on \endash  and she had left her house in Elmdon, and she was retired and living in some flats [in Cambridge]. Well, these flats happened to be at the end of the road where I lived, and \endash  I hope this isn\rquote t all irrelevant - }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
