\par Marilyn:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 And at this stage I had three little ones. My husband\rquote s job was in London, at UCL. I began to pick up t
he connections with Girton College, as a By Fellow, which was very valuable to me, but it wasn\rquote t - it didn\rquote 
t occupy me [entirely]. I was also very friendly with somebody else who had been actually in Papua New Guinea at the same time as myself, called Marianne Leach, the wife of Jerry Leach, who, at that stage, was teaching in the Department \endash 
 nothing to do with Edmund Leach - and I forget, and this is where I really don\rquote t remember now, but I think it was Marianne who began working for Audrey, because Audre
y had all this material on Elmdon that she wanted putting in order. She also worked with a historian called Jean Robin, who produced a parallel historian\rquote 
s account of Elmdon, from the historical records that she, Jean, had very largely, herself, collected.
 [Elmdon: Continuity and Change in a North-West Essex Village, 1861-1964, Cambridge University Press, 1980.] So Jean Robin and Marianne Leach and Audrey - I don\rquote t know, Marianne must have suggested I go visit, I don\rquote 
t know how it happened, but Audrey after
 a while, asked if I would write one of the chapters of her book that she had in mind, to be the end result of all this material that had been collected. I was very happy to do that. But it became clear that I needed to do more than just write the one cha
pter, and eventually I found myself writing the whole thing. It was perfect for me, at that stage, with little children, needing this - as it were, an occupation \endash 
 and also to take me away from some issues in Melanesian anthropology that had got a bit complicated. I mean, that\rquote s another story! In fact, I\rquote ve always been very grateful that I was involved, because I - I was going to say \'93
acquired some insights\'94, but that sounds a bit [pretentious] - but I got to learn a bit about English kinship in a way that I wouldn\rquote t have done at all if I hadn\rquote 
t done this work, so I was very pleased about that. What was odd was that one was dealing not just with one other ethnographer\rquote s materials, one was actually dealing with notebooks and scraps of paper, and files and further researches \endash 
 because Marianne Leach was doing a very thorough job on checking genealogies with public records and so forth. So it was very heterogeneous material in terms of genre, it was heterogeneous in terms of the people who had done it. I should s
ay, in parenthesis, that there was no one [of those who had worked on the Elmdon materials] who, as far as I recall, wasn\rquote 
t happy to have their material used this way, I think everybody we contacted was happy that it might have some use. [But it meant that] everything was seen in terms of the people who, by and large, were youngsters and in training as students. They weren
\rquote t seasoned field-workers. Audrey [had her] own ideas about the about the village and so forth. And I\rquote m afraid I picked my own way throug
h it. I must have discussed, with Audrey, what I was doing, but I did actually make it my own, in terms of its organisation \endash 
 I mean, terms, particularly, of the way I placed kinship in relation to class, which seemed, to me, important. In terms of re-using other people\rquote 
s material, you will appreciate that most of the material was accounts of families and family relations, accounts of property holdings. Because it was very interesting who owned houses, who rented houses, the general perception of the housin
g shortage in Elmdon. [However] there was very little on, for example, how people used the pubs, or the fetes, or public days that were held in Elmdon - not that there were very many of them - so there wasn\rquote 
t a great deal of either observational material on village life, or people\rquote 
s general reflections. It was really a demographic study, partly inspired by the kind of work that was coming on stream from historians of the family, like Peter Laslett and Richard Smith, and Tony Wrigley. Also demographic issues
 were of interest to Jack Goody and so forth in the Department. So it was - I\rquote m trying to avoid using the word \'93fact\'94
 because I think nothing is [a simple] fact! But there was a lot of information about births, marriages and deaths, and handover of propert
y, some disputes would arise in those kinds of context. What people thought about families. And running throughout, of course, was the whole issue of how certain families classified other families in terms of whether they were real Elmdon families or not,
 which had been a conceptual thread that had run through ever since Audrey started the work. Now, I say all that because it wasn\rquote t really a case of re-interpreting other people\rquote 
s interpretations, either on the part of people who were giving information, or on the part of the anthropologist collecting it. Most of the accounts are fairly straightforward descriptions \endash  as you can hear \endash  so the re-use was a bit na\'ef
ve, in that sense. That is, apart from paying attention to when it was collected and realising all the gaps there were, and realising some people had better notes than others, and so on and so forth. I wasn\rquote 
t doing the job of reinterpretation. And that, in a sense, made it quite straightforward, and that\rquote s what really meant I could trace - I could follow my own tracks through the material. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
