\par Elaine:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 Well, that\rquote 
s interesting, because I was going to ask, when you mentioned about the limitations in the material that you had to work with, I was wondering if, at some stage you might have been tempted to go in and do so
me additional research, on your own, to fill the gaps. It sounds like social life was missing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
\par 
\par Marilyn:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
Absolutely. There was something stopping me, that I will tell you about in a moment. But Marianne Leach, however, was doing a lot of checking with, as I say,
 public records and so forth, and that archival material, it seemed to me, was all part of a piece with what had originally been collected. So that was useful archival material. And she and I discussed this use as well. But the other - I\rquote 
m not very proud of this! The other reason, I think, that inhibited me \endash  despite the temptation from actually thinking contrary \endash 
 was that when the theme of class emerged, and when I drew up - formulated - this model, that the way in which people described the village, as t
hat the village has been always there, and the families have been always there, but individuals come and go, and all individuals have contacts elsewhere and including Canada, I mean, not just locally, and when people move between villages, there\rquote 
s a status effect. So that somebody could claim that coming from \endash  not Duddenhoe End, but coming from Saffron Walden, or coming from nearby, maybe it was only five miles away, they could either claim, \'93I\rquote m not a real Elmdoner. I\rquote 
ve come from somewhere else\'94; or other people could say, \'93No, they aren\rquote t real, they\rquote ve come from somewhere else\'94
. So the same action could be either positively or negatively regarded. Well, this is what I thought at the time. That, to my mind, was a model of English class system: the classes
 are there. But, of course, people move up and down. You look at families, and one branch will be upper working class, another branch will be lower middle class, or whatever. And that personal mobility is expressed in Elmdon, in geographical terms. Person
al mobility is very much a theme of classes, yet the classes are static. The material was 1960s remember, I wouldn\rquote t have done the same thing, I\rquote 
m sure, now. I just thought that this was very interesting. But coming back to your question, what inhibited me 
is that I knew that I was introducing a set of topics. I was making a connection between class and village life, that the villagers would not recognise in the way that I set it up, and I didn\rquote 
t want - I thought it would, in fact, I thought it would be insulting. It would be a bit insulting to tell people who have their own ways of talking about what\rquote s important to the village, and what\rquote s real and what isn\rquote 
t real, and so forth, I just thought that making the class dimension explicit would not go down at all well with anyone. Now, I should have put it to the test, but I didn\rquote t. I hope that people, these days, have more courage than I did. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
