\par Elaine:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 And you weren\rquote t wanting to delve a bit more into social life at the time either? You talk about the pub, the life at the pub \'85
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
\par 
\par Marilyn:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 No, that was where I thought that there was a certain coherence to the data. I didn\rquote 
t want to disturb that. But there was one drawback, major drawback, I thought, to working from - yes, you said there aren\rquote t many secondary materials \endash  I was treating them like primary materials, and that\rquote 
s a very very good point. But there was one way in which they were secondary, and you said, \'93Yes, because you didn\rquote t collect it\'94 - you then went off on a diversion. So let me come back to that point. Let me tell you an anecdote, and then you
\rquote ll hear the force of what I\rquote m going to say. It may even be in that [Macfarlane] interview, I don\rquote t know. When I was in Papua New Guinea, the third time round, just before returning to the UK, we\rquote 
d lived in Port Moresby, the capital, and I did a study of Hagen, of migrants from the [PNG] Highlands, who were in the city. And I got to know them, and I was really pleased to have done so, because the city was very alienating
, but knowing these people gave me a map of the city. I did appreciate it. There was a large-scale survey \endash  I was doing this small anthropological study \endash 
 there was a large-scale survey going on [at the same time] by some economists who wanted to find out the reasons for migration, and they wanted to find out the economics of migration \endash 
 why people came to the city. So, obviously, one of the things we talked about, I would ask these migrants, \'93Why did you leave home?\'94 And the person would say, \'93I just wanted to\'94. Or the person would say, \'93
Well, there was a lorry going to Lae, and I thought I\rquote d go too \'85\'94 - this was a coastal town - \'85 \'93I thought I\rquote d go to Lae, and then later I found my way to Port Moresby\'94. And then another person would say, \'93Oh, I just though
t it would be a good idea\'94. And I wasn\rquote t getting anywhere. Okay? But then by the time the 14th or 15th person has said, \'93Oh, it\rquote s just my idea\'94, you know, \'93It was in my head\'94
 in this special phrase in the language, which says, \'93It was in my head and I did it\'94. \'93It\rquote s just my [wish],\'94 you suddenly realise, \'93Yes, yes, you\rquote re being told something\'94
. Of course, what they were telling me is, first of all, they do not like making comparisons [between] their economic opportunities in town, and at home, because at home they\rquote 
re cash-cropping, they had subsistence crops. In the town, a lot of them had no jobs, and if they did have jobs, they were unskilled labourers and they had no money. And if they did have money, people would come and take it from them. I mean, peopl
e would come and visit them from home, and take it from them. So first of all, they didn\rquote t want to compare home and town in economic terms. Secondly, they didn\rquote 
t really like thinking about home, because when you think about home, you think about people, you think about your obligations. And the statement, \'93I put it in my mind, when I went to Port Moresby\'94. [\'93I just wanted to go.\'94
] It was actually a statement of autonomy. You know? They were resisting the kinds of claims that could be put on them. They were saying, \'93[Other] people don\rquote t matter\'94. You know, \'93I decided to do it\'94
. And thirdly, what kept people alive in town was a sense of, somehow, they were making their own position. Even the people out of work would speak in terms of, well, perhaps somebody was dismissed from domestic work, and they would say, \'93
Well, this master \'85\'94 \endash  because \'93master\'94 was the term for \'93employer\'94 - \'93Well, this master, he got cross all the time, and I left\'94. Not, \'93I\rquote ve been dismissed\'94. No. So the point is, it was only by, you know,
 hearing it 14, 15, 16, 17, however many times, you suddenly realise, you know, the penny drops, you know? \'93You\rquote re being told something\'94. And it was that repetition of little idioms, or little bits and pieces of people\rquote 
s reflections, that I missed [from the Elmdon material], of course, because they wouldn\rquote 
t be written down. The only constantly repeated thing that was written down, was the history of who or who was not a real Elmdoner, because that was something that Audrey had picked up in exactly the same 
way. Audrey had picked that up, so it [became] the current topic, and she had guided us. So everybody had written notes about the concept of being a real Elmdoner. So that was there, but nothing else was. So I couldn\rquote 
t - in that sense it was very much secondary data. I couldn\rquote t feel those kinds of resonances as I was able to feel in that work in Port Moresby. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
