\par Marilyn:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 Oh, now that\rquote s a very interesting question. I\rquote 
m not sure I would have known how to make kinship an object of study, as it were, just going on my own experience. Afterwards, of course, in a way I re-wrote Elmdon, with the book called, After Nature \endash  and that is ve
ry autobiographical: in the same way, not overtly, but in the same way as I kept the material from Audrey and her students coherent, [treated it as a body of material,] I confined myself, in writing that book, to everything [books, papers, etc] I had in t
he house. I didn\rquote t go outside what I already had, except I borrowed one book from my mother, I think. And I was able to do it. I don\rquote t think I could have done it - I don\rquote 
t think I could have come back to my own understandings of kinship without having first been able to develop a notion of kinship as an object of study, or an object of knowledge by linking it with this issue of the village, in Elmdon. When I refer to \'93
insight\'94, I mean really theoretical and conceptual insights. So that, for example, I was a bit rebellious, I daresay, but I didn\rquote 
t think that the kind of teaching that was being taught in the [then Cambridge] Department - on which, of course, I had drawn hugely in my own previous work in Melanesia, no question - I found that much less stimulatin
g for thinking about this English village than the work of David Schneider, and I deliberately, as it were, followed his cultural analysis of American kinship in thinking about Elmdon. So that was one thing. Another issue, was the fact that the material s
eemed to lend itself to a way of talking about the inseparability of class and kinship that I\rquote 
ve already talked about, and that was a matter of producing a particular model. That had really been started off by all the information that was there on the way [
Elmdon] people picked up on the tiniest discriminations to talk about class and status, because I\rquote m talking about class in terms of - well, it\rquote 
s a mix both of economic class and of the kind of status that people had in the village. So that one could be \endash  as I said before, about coming and going, one could be positive or negative \endash 
 one could be positive or negative about staying as well. There was obviously a lot of historical work that took it down among those four families that defined themselves as real E
lmdon families. They were basically farm labourers, and thinking of this in terms of they having a lien on the farm owners to employ them, so to speak, by being the real Elmdon families \endash  that kind of thing \endash 
 and realising that other families had, in fact, been present in the village before these real Elmdon families arrived, but they were craftsmen or professionals, or people with a variety of occupations \endash 
 not farmers or farm [labourers]. Farmers are a separate category, of course, but not farm labourers \endash  and these people wouldn\rquote t dream of describing themselves as \'93real Elmdon\'94. This was way beyond any personal experience I\rquote 
d had. I mean, this really was new information to me. To which, of course, I added what I\rquote d learnt in Papua New Guinea. What I\rquote d there learnt was that gender \endash  that is the way people thought about men and women \endash 
 had an ideological dimension. This was the mid-1960s, and it seemed the work I\rquote d done on gender analysis - I mean, I\rquote m only now putting this together, making the connection - s
o that prepared me for seeing exactly the sort of positive/negative evaluations of who came, who went, who was \'93real\'94, who was not \'93real. So, for example, somebody who\rquote 
d been away to domestic service - and incidentally, one [Elmdon] person had actually done domestic service in Petts Wood \endash  in the 1920s [where I lived as a girl in the 1940s-50s] \endash - but the women who\rquote 
d been away to domestic service and came back, thought themselves a bit above the farm [workers], the boys, who stayed working on the farm. And 
if you were to just describe the demographics, the daughter of a farm labourer marries the son of a farm labourer, you would say, \'93Well, you know, this is a homogeneous village, isn\rquote 
t it, and everybody marries in the village, and here is the daughter of a farm labourer marrying the son of a farm labourer\'94. [Yet] that daughter regards herself not as marrying an equal. If she marries in the village, she regards herself as \'93
marrying down\'94. So that that description, that apparent homogeneity which you would just get from the bare records, in fact, doesn\rquote t really reflect the way people, themselves, are thinking about status. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
\par 
\par Elaine:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 Interesting. Now, I\rquote m curious to know if you found relationships between that and any of your work in New Guinea? }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
