\par Marilyn:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 Well, only in the rather indirect sense. Now I\rquote m thinking about it, and I\rquote 
m sure this is in the interview, when I was in the Papua New Guinea Highlands there was a great deal of talk about divorce and I thought my thesis was going to be a study of divorce and marital stabil
ity and all the rest of it. And I realised, at a crucial juncture, that what I was hearing, I wasn\rquote 
t hearing a society that suffers a high divorce rate or whatever, I was listening to the fact that people blamed - or the men blamed women for all kinds of troubles that happened between their two clans \endash 
 because the woman travels from one clan to another in marriage. And that how men think about women, and how [women] think about men, was as much symbolic. I mean, the word \'93ideology\'94 wasn\rquote t - symbolic anthrop
ology was just on the horizon, but the word \'93ideology\'94 hadn\rquote t really sedimented in general anthropology. But in essence, I was hearing a gender ideology \endash  although, of course, at that time, the word \'93gender\'94 wasn\rquote 
t used either. \'93Gender\'94 was first in circulation about 1972, and one talked about \'93sex roles\'94 and other things! (LAUGHS) So all I\rquote m saying is that I was alert to some of the nuances in the way in which people talk about one another 
\endash  I guess this is all I\rquote m saying. A kind of indirect connection. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
