\par Marilyn:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 Well, okay. Another way of talking about the book is it\rquote s really the only political book I\rquote ve written. Again, it doesn
\rquote t look like politics. But this was at the height of Margaret Thatcher\rquote s - or what turned out to be towards the end of Margaret Thatcher\rquote s regime - in which we had an emphasis on consumerism, and a huge emphasis on the individual 
\endash  you know, her famous statement about \'93There\rquote s no such thing as society\'94. It seemed, to me, we were being taken in a very particular cultural direction, and yet it was very hard to put your finger on exactly what it was. And she,
 of course, would appeal to tradition - that the English have always traditionally been individualistic, that kind of thing. One of the ideas that came to me is that it actually makes all the difference in the world whether you make that explicit or wheth
er it remains implicit, and as soon as you take up something and make it explicit, you actually change it. And I came up with this [notion], I\rquote m not sure there\rquote 
s not enough depth for it to be really useful, but I came up with this notion that, one way at least, to induce change, or bring about change, is simply to value what you think you already value. So making Traditional \endash  capital T \endash 
 all kinds of things about English life - you put them in a box called \'93Traditional\'94 - takes away their taken for granted 
implicit status. They no longer become part of the fabric, they become part of the superstructure, part of the advertisement, part of the promotion and so on and so forth, but it appears all you\rquote re doing is valuing what you value. It\rquote 
s a very simple little [notion], but it rang true. But anyway, just to finish, I set myself a task of thinking, \'93
How could a Prime Minister not make an equation between the duty of government, and a sense of social fabric, by denying there is such a thing as society, and elevating the individual?\'94 So I wanted to ask myself, \'93
Okay, what makes that statement plausible?\'94 Because people believed her. She was very persuasive, which is why all kinds of cuttings of the time from newspapers and so forth, this sort of thing was taken up.
 I mean, there would be criticism, of course, from the Left, collectivist criticism, but that wasn\rquote 
t the point. The point was, it did not seem an absurd statement. So where, in English culture, what is it she hooked into, that her statement can be believed
? So I went to an arena as far away from politics as you might consider, which is kinship, to find, \'93Okay, so where is the individual?\'94
 And I come up again, with one of these models in which I did a major theoretical work! (LAUGHS) Individuals produce individuals, and that\rquote s my definition of English kinship. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
\par 
\par Elaine:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 Again, you say, their interdependence demonstrates the fact that\rquote s very strong, and I remember thinking, \'93Yes, I hadn\rquote 
t thought of that\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
