body wanted me to comment on what anthropologists thought about egg donation between sisters, and I had to say, \'93As far as I know, anthropologists haven\rquote t thought about egg donation between sisters!\'94
 (LAUGHS) I mean, this came completely out of the blue! A
nd I found myself quite challenged. And it so happened that someone called Michelle Stanworth had just compiled a collection of essays on new reproductive technologies, and it seemed, to me, that there were a lot of issues here for kinship. This, of cours
e
, occurred before After Nature, this is one of the strands that led into After Nature, I deal with some of those issues there. But they continued afterwards, as it were, into the mid-1990s. Then from that, I stumbled across issues to do with intellectual 
property, actually through a court case that had involved - in my head, there are always two competing versions of this \endash  one to do with frozen embryo, and one to do with a surrogacy case, to my embarrassment. What embarrasses me is that it\rquote 
s not fixed in my mind which of these cases it was. But there was a case in which a lawyer was arguing that the commissioning parents \endash  that is the parents who had commissioned the birth of a child \endash 
 should be regarded as conceiving the child in the same way as [natural] parents would conceive a child. Playing \endash  this was in America \endash  but playing on the English double meaning of \'93conceive\'94
- conceive in the mind, and bodily conceive. His argument about ownership through mental conception, having the idea of a child, came dir
ectly from intellectual property law, and this made me sit up. And this was a time when intellectual property issues were travelling through a number of countries in the world, including the US, and Ghana, and [especially in the Third World], people were 
l
atching on to an international recognition of intellectual property, as a solution to conserving cultural heritage. These two things came together in my mind, and then in fact, led me back to Papua New Guinea, and the study of intellectual property issues
 in the context of cultural heritage in Papua New Guinea. So how one\rquote s life follows - but I\rquote ve been very privileged to have been able to follow my own lead, as it were, in a lot of these things. I\rquote 
m privileged in having the opportunity to be able to follow things through. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid857456\charrsid857456 
